WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.980 --> 00:00:03.180
Prof: So back to
business.

00:00:03.180 --> 00:00:07.580
We're in a really great
position here because we've gone

00:00:07.580 --> 00:00:11.980
from one dimension to three
dimensions, to get something

00:00:11.980 --> 00:00:13.740
real, a real atom.
 

00:00:13.740 --> 00:00:16.780
And if you take that table from
last time,

00:00:16.780 --> 00:00:19.120
that we got from the old-time
mathematicians,

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:22.200
and plug in according to what
you can use together,

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:25.790
you get the exact wave function
that's a solution of the

00:00:25.790 --> 00:00:29.120
Schrödinger equation for
the hydrogen atom,

00:00:29.120 --> 00:00:33.920
or any atom that has only one
electron.

00:00:33.920 --> 00:00:37.080
It can have any nuclear charge
you want, right?

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:39.020
So it's the real thing.
 

00:00:39.020 --> 00:00:41.375
People have shown you pictures,
which are some kinds of

00:00:41.375 --> 00:00:44.534
approximations of this,
but you have the equation,

00:00:44.534 --> 00:00:47.820
the actual formula,
for the true wave function,

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:50.450
and no one has a better one
than you have.

00:00:50.450 --> 00:00:53.000
That's the real McCoy.
 

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:53.830
Okay?
 

00:00:53.830 --> 00:00:56.993
And you can check these
pictures that people have drawn

00:00:56.993 --> 00:00:59.220
to see if they're realistic
graphs,

00:00:59.220 --> 00:01:02.820
or whether they're just some
kind of artist's impression,

00:01:02.820 --> 00:01:05.060
or somebody who doesn't know
anything's impression;

00:01:05.060 --> 00:01:07.046
maybe he's not even an artist.
 

00:01:07.046 --> 00:01:07.510
Right?
 

00:01:07.510 --> 00:01:09.819
So you can actually do these.
 

00:01:09.819 --> 00:01:13.528
And many of them are very
simple functions,

00:01:13.528 --> 00:01:16.000
like e^(-r),
right?

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:17.810
You can hardly get easier than
that.

00:01:17.810 --> 00:01:21.379
Okay, but you can also draw
pictures that look just like

00:01:21.379 --> 00:01:24.950
what you could see if the
electron had a color to it.

00:01:24.950 --> 00:01:29.080
They're done by ray tracing
where the computer pretends it's

00:01:29.080 --> 00:01:33.140
your eye and sees how much
density it would go through,

00:01:33.140 --> 00:01:35.080
if it went through this point
or that point or that point,

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:38.340
along a certain ray from your
eye, and puts a color here

00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:41.840
that's proportional to how much
electron density it sees.

00:01:41.840 --> 00:01:44.515
It's not the wave function;
it's the square of the wave

00:01:44.515 --> 00:01:47.181
function, the electron density,
that Atom-in-a-Box

00:01:47.181 --> 00:01:47.610
plots.
 

00:01:47.610 --> 00:01:48.700
Okay?
 

00:01:48.700 --> 00:01:50.650
So that's what it would really
look like,

00:01:50.650 --> 00:01:54.265
if you could see it and if
there weren't problems with

00:01:54.265 --> 00:01:58.562
wavelength and photons knocking
electrons to kingdom come and so

00:01:58.562 --> 00:01:59.040
on.
 

00:01:59.040 --> 00:02:00.849
That's what it would look like,
right?

00:02:00.849 --> 00:02:04.296
But it'll be colored;
it'll be colored according to

00:02:04.296 --> 00:02:06.049
the sign the wave function has.
 

00:02:06.049 --> 00:02:07.941
It's not the wave function;
it's the square of the wave

00:02:07.941 --> 00:02:08.240
function.
 

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:09.908
So it would be positive.
 

00:02:09.908 --> 00:02:12.610
But it's colored to say the
wave function in this region

00:02:12.610 --> 00:02:14.919
would be positive or in this
region negative.

00:02:14.919 --> 00:02:18.048
And I'll show it to you in just
a second, but first let's -- or

00:02:18.048 --> 00:02:20.419
a few minutes -- but first let's
describe it.

00:02:20.419 --> 00:02:24.145
So there's lots of information
on the screen that you get with

00:02:24.145 --> 00:02:25.550
Atom-in-a-Box.
 

00:02:25.550 --> 00:02:28.490
How many of you have tried it?
 

00:02:28.490 --> 00:02:30.689
Okay, all of you should.
 

00:02:30.689 --> 00:02:31.770
Okay?
 

00:02:31.770 --> 00:02:33.990
Okay, first you have the
Schrödinger equation.

00:02:33.990 --> 00:02:36.902
That always appears and it's
sort of silly but if you need

00:02:36.902 --> 00:02:39.102
the Schrödinger equation
for reference,

00:02:39.102 --> 00:02:39.919
there it is.
 

00:02:39.919 --> 00:02:44.562
Then up at the top is the
particular function that's being

00:02:44.562 --> 00:02:47.147
plotted,
and it's given as n,

00:02:47.147 --> 00:02:50.297
l and m,
and also the nickname

00:02:50.297 --> 00:02:53.199
1s, for this particular
one,

00:02:53.199 --> 00:02:57.150
which is 1,0,0 for n,
l and m.

00:02:57.150 --> 00:03:00.406
And then there's the formula
that that particular wave

00:03:00.406 --> 00:03:02.566
function has,
and you know what it is,

00:03:02.566 --> 00:03:06.144
it's a bunch of constants,
which we can forget,

00:03:06.144 --> 00:03:08.788
but it's e^(-r).
 

00:03:08.788 --> 00:03:10.818
He's not using Ï 
here, notice.

00:03:10.818 --> 00:03:15.596
He uses actual r and
puts in explicitly the Z

00:03:15.596 --> 00:03:20.289
and the a_o,
and the two is cancelled.

00:03:20.289 --> 00:03:20.990
Okay?
 

00:03:20.990 --> 00:03:23.431
And then he says what the
energy would be,

00:03:23.431 --> 00:03:25.158
in units of electron volts.
 

00:03:25.158 --> 00:03:28.961
An electron volt is 23.06 times
as big as a kilocalorie,

00:03:28.961 --> 00:03:31.378
which is what we usually talk
in.

00:03:31.378 --> 00:03:35.407
Now, you can look at these
pictures and ask questions,

00:03:35.407 --> 00:03:39.589
some fairly simple questions,
like where is the electron

00:03:39.589 --> 00:03:41.110
density highest?
 

00:03:41.110 --> 00:03:43.211
The nucleus is in the center of
this picture,

00:03:43.211 --> 00:03:44.120
not surprisingly.
 

00:03:44.120 --> 00:03:45.810
So this is not a hard question.
 

00:03:45.810 --> 00:03:48.650
Where's the electron density
highest?

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:49.990
Prof: In the middle,
right?

00:03:49.990 --> 00:03:51.289
No big surprise there.
 

00:03:51.289 --> 00:03:54.160
Okay, how do you know?
 

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:57.615
You take the wave function,
you square it and find out

00:03:57.615 --> 00:04:01.340
where it has a maximum,
and e^(-distance) has a

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:03.710
maximum when the distance is
zero;

00:04:03.710 --> 00:04:05.219
the value is one.
 

00:04:05.219 --> 00:04:06.688
It falls off from there.
 

00:04:06.688 --> 00:04:09.441
Okay, so you just,
to find where the density is

00:04:09.441 --> 00:04:13.090
highest, you just square the
wave function and maximize it.

00:04:13.090 --> 00:04:18.007
Okay, now but here's a slightly
different question:

00:04:18.007 --> 00:04:21.449
What is the most likely
distance?

00:04:21.449 --> 00:04:24.860
Can you see why that's a
different question than where --

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:27.894
you might think the most likely
distance is wherever the density

00:04:27.894 --> 00:04:30.069
is highest,
but that's not quite true.

00:04:30.069 --> 00:04:30.959
Do you see why?
 

00:04:30.959 --> 00:04:40.339
Student: 
&gt;

00:04:40.339 --> 00:04:41.529
Prof: Because what's
most-- yes?

00:04:41.529 --> 00:04:43.709
Student:  It could be
moving very quickly in the area.

00:04:43.709 --> 00:04:44.632
Prof: No,
it doesn't have to do with

00:04:44.632 --> 00:04:44.829
motion.
 

00:04:44.829 --> 00:04:45.569
Yes Lucas?
 

00:04:45.569 --> 00:04:47.490
Student:  There's almost
no volume in the center.

00:04:47.490 --> 00:04:50.040
Prof: There's almost no
volume in the center.

00:04:50.040 --> 00:04:53.519
If you take--say if you talk
about a point,

00:04:53.519 --> 00:04:56.170
then there's no volume at all.
 

00:04:56.170 --> 00:04:57.480
Okay?
 

00:04:57.480 --> 00:04:59.629
But take a little box and put
it in the center,

00:04:59.629 --> 00:05:02.528
or actually a sphere of a
certain radius,

00:05:02.528 --> 00:05:05.720
a small radius,
0.0001 Å

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:08.305
say,
and put it in the center,

00:05:08.305 --> 00:05:10.920
and see how much density is
inside.

00:05:10.920 --> 00:05:11.500
Okay?
 

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:15.153
But then you could look at one
angstrom out,

00:05:15.153 --> 00:05:19.915
and now you're looking at a
little spherical shell that's

00:05:19.915 --> 00:05:22.040
0.0001 Å
thick.

00:05:22.040 --> 00:05:23.209
Is everybody clear?
 

00:05:23.209 --> 00:05:26.574
So there could be different
directions in which you have

00:05:26.574 --> 00:05:29.574
this electron density,
which is at that particular

00:05:29.574 --> 00:05:31.410
distance from the nucleus.
 

00:05:31.410 --> 00:05:37.459
And the further out you go,
the more volume this shell has.

00:05:37.459 --> 00:05:41.339
It's always the same thickness,
but as you move out there's

00:05:41.339 --> 00:05:42.610
more stuff in it.
 

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:43.769
You see what I mean?
 

00:05:43.769 --> 00:05:45.430
More volume in it.
 

00:05:45.430 --> 00:05:47.259
What's it proportional to?
 

00:05:47.259 --> 00:05:50.050
As you increase r,
how does the volume of the

00:05:50.050 --> 00:05:50.980
shell increase?
 

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:54.079
How does the surface of the
sphere increase as you go out?

00:05:54.079 --> 00:05:55.160
Student:  r^(3).
 

00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:57.089
Prof: No,
volume is r^(3).

00:05:57.089 --> 00:05:58.100
Student:  r^(2).
 

00:05:58.100 --> 00:05:59.170
Prof: It goes with
r^(2).

00:05:59.170 --> 00:06:01.007
The surface goes with
r^(2).

00:06:01.007 --> 00:06:01.439
Right?
 

00:06:01.439 --> 00:06:06.750
So you have to multiply the
probability density by

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:11.410
r^(2),
to see at what radius you have

00:06:11.410 --> 00:06:13.470
the most stuff.
 

00:06:13.470 --> 00:06:16.480
Is that clear to everyone?
 

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:18.653
Because you want to count
everything that's at that

00:06:18.653 --> 00:06:19.776
radius,
not only in that direction but

00:06:19.776 --> 00:06:21.452
also in that direction,
that direction,

00:06:21.452 --> 00:06:23.509
that direction,
and so on,

00:06:23.509 --> 00:06:25.839
and the sphere gets bigger as
you go out.

00:06:25.839 --> 00:06:30.858
So you'll notice that what's
given in this plot here on the

00:06:30.858 --> 00:06:36.310
bottom right is r^(2)
times the wave function squared.

00:06:36.310 --> 00:06:38.040
Okay?
 

00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:43.250
So that'll tell you what's the
most likely distance.

00:06:43.250 --> 00:06:44.110
Okay?
 

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:47.370
So you have to do surface
weighting by r^(2),

00:06:47.370 --> 00:06:51.654
and it's not at zero,
it's at the unit that we use to

00:06:51.654 --> 00:06:55.586
measure distance in,
a_0, which turns out to

00:06:55.586 --> 00:07:00.009
be half an angstrom,
0.53 Å.

00:07:00.009 --> 00:07:03.829
Okay, now here's a 2s
orbital.

00:07:03.829 --> 00:07:04.680
Right?
 

00:07:04.680 --> 00:07:10.471
Here we'll draw two different
shells of the same thickness,

00:07:10.471 --> 00:07:11.269
right?
 

00:07:11.269 --> 00:07:15.016
We'll number them one and two,
and we're going to ask the

00:07:15.016 --> 00:07:17.759
question, which one has higher
density?

00:07:17.759 --> 00:07:29.339
&lt;&lt;Technical adjustments
of room lighting&gt;&gt;

00:07:29.339 --> 00:07:32.269
Okay, which shell has higher
density, one or two?

00:07:32.269 --> 00:07:32.920
Student:  One.
 

00:07:32.920 --> 00:07:35.639
Prof: One, clearly, okay?
 

00:07:35.639 --> 00:07:38.839
Now, here's a different
question -- okay,

00:07:38.839 --> 00:07:43.480
it shows one -- which shell
contains more electron density,

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:44.680
more stuff?
 

00:07:44.680 --> 00:07:46.829
Which one has more probability?
 

00:07:46.829 --> 00:07:47.720
Students:  Two.
 

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:52.103
Prof: It's not obvious,
because one has higher density

00:07:52.103 --> 00:07:53.930
but two is much bigger.
 

00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:54.810
Okay?
 

00:07:54.810 --> 00:07:59.964
And in fact,
the two has about three times

00:07:59.964 --> 00:08:02.228
the radius of one.
 

00:08:02.228 --> 00:08:03.360
Right?
 

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:07.120
So how much more volume does
that shell have?

00:08:07.120 --> 00:08:08.329
Student:  Nine times.
 

00:08:08.329 --> 00:08:10.240
Prof: About nine times
more volume;

00:08:10.240 --> 00:08:12.660
not of the sphere but of the
shell.

00:08:12.660 --> 00:08:13.910
Okay?
 

00:08:13.910 --> 00:08:15.930
So it's about nine times the
volume.

00:08:15.930 --> 00:08:19.427
So it turns out that actually
two has more stuff,

00:08:19.427 --> 00:08:21.613
and you see that in this plot.
 

00:08:21.613 --> 00:08:22.269
Right?
 

00:08:22.269 --> 00:08:27.807
The red for two is bigger than
the green for one.

00:08:27.807 --> 00:08:28.730
Right?
 

00:08:28.730 --> 00:08:33.106
So depending on what question
you ask, you have to decide

00:08:33.106 --> 00:08:37.952
whether you have to weight it by
r^(2) to get the answer

00:08:37.952 --> 00:08:38.970
you need.
 

00:08:38.970 --> 00:08:42.990
Okay, now here's another way of
looking at a wave function.

00:08:42.990 --> 00:08:49.870
This happens to be the -- it's
actually a 3D wave function;

00:08:49.870 --> 00:08:53.230
as you see, not from here,
but from here,

00:08:53.230 --> 00:08:54.070
