two one-electron wave functions?

00:42:45.329 --> 00:42:47.940
Because we have one-electron
wave functions cold;

00:42:47.940 --> 00:42:50.619
we look in the table and we've
got the exact thing.

00:42:50.619 --> 00:42:54.030
If we could take two of those
and multiply them together,

00:42:54.030 --> 00:43:00.974
so orbital A for electron one
times orbital B for electron two

00:43:00.974 --> 00:43:03.172
--
remember, what these things are

00:43:03.172 --> 00:43:04.130
is just numbers.
 

00:43:04.130 --> 00:43:07.661
If you put in some value of
position of electron one and

00:43:07.661 --> 00:43:10.360
some value of position of
electron two,

00:43:10.360 --> 00:43:12.110
this first thing will give you
a number,

00:43:12.110 --> 00:43:13.980
the second thing will give you
a number.

00:43:13.980 --> 00:43:16.947
If you could multiply those two
numbers together and get the

00:43:16.947 --> 00:43:18.860
number for the total wave
function,

00:43:18.860 --> 00:43:22.429
that would be really great,
because then you'd know how to

00:43:22.429 --> 00:43:22.929
